Selective permeability is a process used by cells to control the movement of substances across the cell membrane, as it allows for certain substances to be admitted while preventing others from passing through.

Passive transport occurs when substances move in and out of a cell without the use of energy, and is usually used to move particles from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration.
Osmosis is the diffusion of water molecules across the cell membrane, which works to balance the internal ion concentrations and pH levels.

Facilitated diffusion involves the aid of carrier proteins that help facilitate the movement of substances across the cell membrane, allowing for particles that would otherwise not be able to pass through to enter or leave the cell.
Active transport occurs when a cell uses energy to move a substance against its concentration gradient, usually from an area of low concentration to an area of high concentration.
Pumps are specialized proteins that help move charged particles like sodium and potassium ions across the membrane using energy.

Membrane-assisted transport happens when vesicles formed around large molecules are fused with the cell membrane, forcing them out of the cell as in exocytosis, or when they are engulfed by the cell membrane as in endocytosis, phagocytosis, or pinocytosis.
Protein channels or channel proteins allow for specific molecules or substances to pass through the cell membrane into or out of a cell.

Selective permeability is used by the cell membrane to allow certain substances to pass through with minimal effort (and sometimes none at all). Passive transport, on the other hand, relies on the concentration gradient of molecules to move from high to low areas.

Osmosis is an example of passive transport where water molecules diffuse across the membrane in order to balance out the concentrations between both sides. Facilitated diffusion also requires energy but instead uses carrier proteins to help move molecules from one side of the membrane to the other.

Active transport, however, uses energy (usually from ATP) to move substances from lower to higher concentration, or against the concentration gradient. This type of transport is necessary when there is a need for a substance inside the cell that cannot be acquired by diffusion.

Pumps are specialized transporters that use energy and carrier proteins to actively move charged particles like sodium and potassium ions through membranes. Membrane-assisted transport can also occur when vesicles form around large molecules such as in phagocytosis, pinocytosis, exocytosis, and endocytosis.

Finally, protein channels or channel proteins are used to selectively allow specific molecules or substances into or out of a cell. This type of transport requires little energy and may require no energy at all.

Selective permeability, passive transport, and osmosis are processes used by cells to control the movement of substances across the cell membrane. Through selective permeability, the cell membrane can allow some substances to move while blocking others. Passive transport moves substances from an area of higher concentration to an area of lower concentration. Osmosis is the diffusion of water across the cell membrane.

Facilitated diffusion, active transport, and pumps are processes used by cells to manage the movement of substances across the cell membrane. Facilitated diffusion occurs when the cell membrane controls the passage of a particle into or out of a cell. Active transport requires energy for a substance to move from an area of low to high concentration, or against the concentration gradient. Pumps move charged particles like sodium and potassium ions through membranes using energy and carrier proteins.

Membrane-assisted transport, protein channels, and channel proteins are processes used by cells to regulate the flow of substances across the cell membrane. Membrane-assisted transport happens when vesicles are formed around large molecules, liquid droplets, or when the membrane fuses with the cell membrane forcing large molecules out of the cell. Protein channels or channel proteins allow for specific molecules and substances into or out of the cell.

Facilitated diffusion utilizes carrier proteins and channels to move particles through the cell membrane, while active transport requires energy in order to move molecules from an area of lower concentration to an area of higher concentration. Pumps can be used to move specific ions like sodium and potassium through the membrane with energy and carrier proteins.
